				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">In I.P.O., a Quest to Satisfy China&#8217;s Appetite for Pork</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Neil Gough			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-04-10T05:01:13+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">April 10, 2014 1:01 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">April 10, 2014 1:01 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/11/business/PORK/PORK-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/11/business/PORK/PORK-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/11/business/PORK/PORK-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002819368" width="592" height="337" alt="A pork market in Hefei. China consumes nearly half of all the worldâs pork production."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="337"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A pork market in Hefei. China consumes nearly half of all the worldâs pork production.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Jianan Yu/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/04/10/china-pork-companys-listing-could-raise-more-than-5-billion/" data-title="In I.P.O., a Quest to Satisfy China&#8217;s Appetite for Pork" data-description="The public offering of WH Group will offer investors a chance to bet on a business that is trying to marry Chinaâs apparently insatiable demand for the meat with the efficiency of American pork production.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">HONG KONG &#8212; There is a commodity creating ravenous demand among Chinaâs growing consumer class, one whose pricing is so important that it influences the Chinese central bankâs monetary policy. The commerce ministry even maintains strategic reserves and has been piling them higher in recent weeks in an attempt to stabilize prices.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Pork prices, that is.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Fresh, chilled and frozen; salted, smoked and brined; chops, bellies, rumps, feet â nobody consumes pigs like the Chinese. The country accounts for about half of the 109 million tons of pork that will be produced and eaten globally this year, according to the United States Department of Agriculture.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Now, one company is trying to marry Chinaâs apparently insatiable demand for the meat with the efficiency of American pork production. On Thursday, the Chinese pork company that bought Smithfield Foods, Americaâs biggest pork producer, formally began an attempt to raise as much as 41.2 billion Hong Kong dollars, or $5.3 billion, by listing the enlarged business in Hong Kong.</p>
<div class="w225 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/11/business/11pork_graphic/11pork_graphic-blog225.gif" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/11/business/11pork_graphic/11pork_graphic-blog225.gif" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/11/business/11pork_graphic/11pork_graphic-blog225.gif" id="100000002819982" width="225" height="310" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="310"><meta itemprop="width" content="225"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When Shuanghui International paid $4.7 billion in cash for Smithfield last year, it was the biggest buyout ever of an American company by a Chinese company. The combined business has since been renamed WH Group, and its initial public offering would be the largest in the world since that of a Brazilian insurer, BB Seguridade Participacoes, in April 2013.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">With the deal, WH Group is betting that it can take advantage of lower costs in the United States. Despite the tremendous size of Chinaâs pork market and the lower cost of labor, China greatly lags the United States in the efficiency with which it can produce the meat.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âCosts in the U.S. are 60 percent of Chinaâs; in the beginning I thought that was counterintuitive,â Wu Shangzhi, chairman of the Chinese private equity group CDH Investments, said in January at an investment forum in Hong Kong. CDH bought a minority stake in Shuanghui in 2006 alongside Goldman Sachs and today is the biggest single shareholder of WH Group, with a 38 percent stake before the I.P.O., according to the companyâs preliminary listing document.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Wu told the forum he had been struck by the opportunity to export pork from the United States. Average hog prices in China were 1.65 times as high as those in the United States from 2010 to 2012, according to WHâs stock exchange filings.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âDuring the Cultural Revolution I went to the countryside,â Mr. Wu said. âI raised my pig in the backyard. The cost was zero to me at that time. But times change. In an integrated global economy the comparative advantage certainly points in a different direction.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">WH also wants to leverage the Smithfield acquisition in an operational way, to increase the efficiency of its slaughtering plants in China. Last year, the companyâs utilization rate at its Chinese slaughtering plants was only 72 percent of their capacity. In the United States, the comparable rate at Smithfieldâs plants was 97 percent, according to WHâs listing document.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Pork costs more in China because feed grain prices are higher and hogs are raised on a much smaller scale than in the United States. In the United States, farms with an annual production of 3,000 hogs or more account for about 83 percent of overall production. In China, such large-scale hog farms account for only about 2.5 percent of the countryâs production.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At the same time, worsening soil and water pollution and rising urbanization rates are threatening Chinaâs supply of arable land for growing hog feed, which contributes to increasingly volatile pork prices. Food safety scandals remain an almost daily concern for ordinary Chinese, and the domestic pork industry has been no exception.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Securing a safe and stable supply of pork and closely monitoring prices have become important tasks for policy makers in China. Pork is a major component of consumer price inflation there, and as such, it is a factor that affects how the countryâs central bank sets monetary policy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Domestic hog prices have fallen about 50 percent in the last two months, according to a report on Monday on Chinaâs central television broadcaster. This is easing inflationary pressures in China, giving policy makers more room to provide liquidity to other struggling areas of the economy as growth falls to its slowest pace in over a decade â for now, at least.</p>
<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/11/business/Porkjp/Porkjp-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/11/business/Porkjp/Porkjp-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/11/business/Porkjp/Porkjp-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002819508" width="592" height="361" alt="A supermarket in Hangzhou, China. The Chinese pork company that bought Smithfield Foods is going public in Hong Kong."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="361"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A supermarket in Hangzhou, China. The Chinese pork company that bought Smithfield Foods is going public in Hong Kong.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> China Daily, via Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAmple pig stocks suggest that pork prices, the most important determinant of food inflation, are likely to remain weak over the coming months,â Qinwei Wang and Julian Evans-Pritchard, China economists at Britainâs Capital Economics, wrote in a research note this week. âBeyond that, the outlook is less promising. Pig farmers, many of whom are making losses at current prices, have begun to cut pig numbers, which suggests that a rebound in pork prices late this year is possible.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In recent months, local ministry of commerce officials across Chinaâs interior provinces have been seizing on falling hog prices to increase the countryâs strategic reserves of chilled and frozen pork. But because such reserves are generally tiny when compared with Chinaâs overall consumption of the meat, and because frozen pork lasts only for several months, the commerce ministryâs buying tends not to have a major effect on domestic pork price trends.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Despite the opportunities, WH Group faces a number of challenges. For one, it is heavily indebted from the money it borrowed to acquire Smithfield last year. WHâs total debt rose from $194 million at the end of 2012 to $7.4 billion at the end of last year as a result of the deal. The proceeds from the I.P.O., which is expected to value the company at $15.1 billion to $21.2 billion, will help pay that down, but the most the company stands to pocket would be $4.2 billion. Anything else would go to existing shareholders who are selling.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The term sheet was unclear on which shareholders were selling. In addition to CDH Investments, Goldman Sachs and the companyâs management, WHâs other big shareholders include the Singapore state investor, Temasek Holdings, and New Horizon Capital, a private equity firm co-founded by the son of the former Chinese prime minister Wen Jiabao.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Another complicating factor is Chinaâs recent record of food safety scandals, which have made the public increasingly wary of domestic meat, produce and other foodstuffs â and spurred regulators to action. In 2011, reports in the local Chinese media accused one of WHâs factories of sourcing hogs whose feed included clenbuterol hydrochloride, an adrenal nervous stimulant known as âlean meat powderâ in China, but which is banned in the country. The company closed the plant for more than two months for inspections but found no traces of the adulterant. Still, WH says, sales slumped that year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">More recently, Chinese regulators have imposed temporary restrictions on the importation of live hogs from the United States because of an outbreak of Porcine Epidemic Diarrhea virus that started to take hold among American pigs last year. Media reports this month said that China would suspend imports of such hogs until stricter testing protocols are developed, a move that applies only to live animals, not meat.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">WH must also wean itself off the use of an adulterant that is widespread in the United States but banned in China. Ractopamine, a feed additive that makes meat leaner, is currently used in more than 80 percent of hogs raised in the United States and has been said to increase instances of injury among live pigs. WH plans to reduce its use of the chemical, but the company warns that the transition will increase costs that may not be recouped.</p>
<footer class="story-footer">
